artists.biography:
Eldest of four children, Charles, Victor and Roger. Seu Jorge had a hard childhood, but in the quiet neighborhood of Ema Gogó in Belford Roxo. He began working with ten years of age in a tire, first of several occupations as continuous, joiner and potato peeler in a bar. He served the Brazilian Army in 1989-1990, in Rio de Janeiro, the Armament Depot Center - DCArmt, made ​​in the course of military bugler 2nd Battalion Motorized Infantry School (DALY Regiment), but not adapted to military life, being licensed in January 1990.
The various professions never overshadowed his real desire to become a musician. Since teenager, attended wheels Rio samba accompanying his father and brothers in funk parties and dances charms the periphery, and soon began to professionalize singing at night. That's when the death of his brother Victor in a massacre led to the disintegration family, Seu Jorge and eventually became homeless for about three years. The turning point came when the clarinetist Paulo Moura invited him to audition for a musical theater. It was eventually approved and participating in more than 20 shows with Teatro University of Rio de Janeiro, as a singer and actor.

Seu Jorge.biography:

He served the Brazilian Army in 1989-1990, in Rio de Janeiro, the Armament Depot Center - DCArmt, made ​​in the course of military bugler 2nd Battalion Motorized Infantry School (DALY Regiment), but not adapted to military life, being licensed in January 1990.
The various professions never overshadowed his real desire to become a musician. Since teenager, attended wheels Rio samba accompanying his father and brothers in funk parties and dances charms the periphery, and soon began to professionalize singing at night. That's when the death of his brother Victor in a massacre led to the disintegration family, Seu Jorge and eventually became homeless for about three years. release_name_apple_music: The Life Aquatic - Studio Sessions featuring Seu Jorge

apple_music.editorial_notes: The master samba-revivalist Seu Jorge is talented enough to tackle any genre of music and refashion it in his own image. He first gained international attention through his role in the critically acclaimed City of God, then 2005’s Cru (Raw) saw him remake Lieber and Stoller’s standard “Don’t” into sunny Brazilian Pop. It's not surprising that American auteur Wes Anderson recognized Jorge’s interpretive talents and commissioned him to record a set of Portuguese language David Bowie covers for the soundtrack to his Life Aquatic. What is surprising is the fierce originality that Jorge injects into his performances. His effortlessly supple delivery, reminiscent at times of Caetano Veloso’s dulcet croon, and his painterly rhythm guitar work allow The Life Aquatic Studio Sessions to transcend its admittedly kitschy concept; Jorge’s unrestrained covers of “Lady Stardust” and “Life on Mars” in particular gain strength when removed from their cinematic context. With The Life Aquatic Studio Sessions Seu Jorge has created a work possessed of a casual intimacy that makes it an essential addition to his catalogue.

editorialNotes.short: David Bowie’s catalogue gets a bossa nova makeover.
